title: R2_Noam_FirstMeeting_CopyR1
tags: #run_2 #day_1 #scene #char_Noam #loc_Dataroom
---
<<bg bg_backend>>
<<bgm darkwave_short_version_1>>

Back corner office. Monitors everywhere—three on the desk, two on a stand, one balanced on a stack of server documentation.

Noam spins in his chair, mug in hand. The mug says "I SURVIVED ANOTHER MEETING THAT SHOULD HAVE BEEN AN EMAIL."

Noam: Did you put in a help ticket?

Player: What? No. Nothing's broken. You invited me.

Noam: Right, right. I do that sometimes.

He doesn't sound convinced by his own explanation.

Noam: I'm Noam. Data Science, IT, sysadmin, occasional therapist for anyone whose laptop does something they don't like.

Player: That sounds exhausting.

Noam: It's a lifestyle. The monitors help. Each one shows something different. This one's system health. This one's engagement flows. That one's a nature documentary. I find it calms me between crises.

He gestures at the screen with the documentary. A bird is diving for fish. It misses.

Noam: See? Even birds fail sometimes. Comforting.

Player: You invited me here for bird facts?

Noam: I flagged your handle because you're new. New either means "too scared to cause problems" or "too naive to know you're causing them."

Player: Which one am I?

Noam: Jury's still out.

He taps a few keys. A small UI element appears on your console—a thin horizontal bar, currently empty, labeled "OVERSIGHT INDEX."

Noam: Welcome gift. Suspicion HUD. Tells you how much attention you're attracting from Compliance, security, the people who decide whether your badge works tomorrow.

Player: Why would I need that?

Noam: Right now? You don't. You're a good employee doing good employee things. Bar stays at zero.

He leans back. His chair squeaks.

Noam: But if you ever start... exploring. Asking questions you shouldn't ask. Poking at corners of the system that prefer to stay unlit. This tells you how close you are to someone noticing.

Player: Is that common? People... poking?

Noam: More common than you'd think. Less successful than they'd hope.

He says it like a weather report. Partly cloudy, chance of disappearance.

Player: Are you warning me?

Noam: I'm orienting you. There's a difference. Warnings imply I know something bad is coming. Orientations just show you where the walls are.

He spins back to his monitors. The subject change is so abrupt it feels intentional.

Noam: You play pickleball?

Player: Not really.

Noam: You should. Great cardio. Excellent for networking with people who control your access permissions.

The nature documentary bird finally catches a fish. Noam nods at the screen.

Noam: See? Persistence.

<<set $noam_met = true>>
<<set $r2_noam_met = true>>
