title: R2_Dina_FirstMeeting_CopyR1
tags: #run_2 #day_1 #scene #char_Dina #loc_Breakroom
---
<<bg bg_breakroom>>
<<bgm darkwave_short_version_1>>

The vending machine hums with resigned energy. Dina's jabbing buttons with focused intensity.

Dina: Give me the granola bar. I know you have twelve.

The machine drops orange chips instead. She stares at them.

Dina: This is not what I asked for.

She turns, notices you.

Dina: You must be the new handle.

Player: That obvious?

Dina: You still have hope in your eyes. I'm Dina.

She offers a handshake—firm, efficient.

Player: How long have you been here?

Dina: Three restructurings, two CEO transitions, and one incident we legally can't discuss.

Player: How's your user?

She sighs.

Dina: [STATIC BURST]—decided three a.m. was the perfect time to draft a novella-length message to her ex-boyfriend. Engagement through the roof. My sanity metrics look like someone fell down a flight of stairs.

Player: Is that... good?

Dina: Depends who you ask. Leadership sees the engagement spike and thinks I'm a genius. I see a woman typing "I miss you" forty-seven different ways and think about retirement.

She opens the orange chips despite herself. Eats one. Makes a face.

Dina: These taste like betrayal. Want some?

Player: I'm good.

Dina: Smart.

She glances toward Arthur's glass office.

Dina: How's Arthur treating you?

Player: Fine. Tired, but fine.

Dina: He's always tired now.

She eats another chip, considering something.

Dina: When I started, Arthur had a whiteboard in his office covered in ideas. "Ethical Engagement Frameworks." Proposals to make the metrics actually mean something. He'd corner executives in the elevator, pitch them on reforms. Wrote memos. Built prototypes on his own time.

Player: What happened?

Dina: Nothing happened. That's the thing. Nothing happened, over and over, for years. The memos got filed. The prototypes got shelved. The whiteboard got erased.

She pauses.

Dina: There was a guy, back then. Younger than Arthur. Asked a lot of questions. Kept digging into things the system preferred to leave buried.

Player: What happened to him?

Dina: He's not on the leaderboard anymore.

She says it flat. Like it's not a story, just a fact.

Dina: Arthur stopped asking questions after that. Started going to his kid's debate tournaments. Started eating his wife's sandwiches even though there's too much mayonnaise. Started being the kind of guy who survives.

She crumples the chip bag.

Dina: The building doesn't break you all at once. It just waits.

She pulls out her phone, shows you her credit balance. The number is absurd.

Dina: Anyway. Welcome-to-the-floor gift. I've been here long enough that my fake money has accumulated into fake wealth. I can spare some credits, or—

She reaches behind the microwave and pulls out a small, dense piece of split firewood.

Dina: I've got oak. Seasoned two years. Someone keeps stealing it from my yard—I'm conducting an investigation—but this piece is safe.

Player: You're offering me... firewood.

Dina: I'm offering you options. Credits are useful now. Firewood is useful later, in ways you won't understand until you need it.

-> Take credits
    <<set $dina_gift_choice = "credits">>
    <<set $rapid_feedback_cash += 15>>
    <<set $dina_friendliness += 1>>
